Load book

We will use * Frankenstein; or, the Modern Prometheus*, by Mary Shelley (Gutenberg Project):

raw_book <- list.files(path = "./", pattern = "Frankenstein.txt", full.names = T) %>% 
        map_chr(~ read_file(.)) %>% 
        str_replace_all("", "'") %>% 
        str_replace_all("'s\\b", "") %>% 
        data_frame(text = .)
## In case we are analyzing several books at once:
## Enumerate books
# raw_book <- raw_book %>% 
#   mutate(linenumber = row_number(),
#          book = cumsum(str_detect(text, regex("^NP: .+",
#                                                  ignore_case = TRUE)))) %>%
#   ungroup()
# Tidy book by tokenizing
tidy_book <- raw_book %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text) 
# Load stop words in English
data(stop_words)
# Remove stop words
tidy_book <- tidy_book %>%
  anti_join(stop_words)
Joining, by = "word"

Lemmatize book

Find the lemma for all the words:

lemma_book <- tidy_book %>% 
  mutate(word = lemmatize_words(word))
tidy_book %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) 
lemma_book %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)

Sentiment analysis

Score each word according to the general lexicon from Bing Liu and collaborators

lemma_book %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%
  acast(word ~ sentiment, value.var = "n", fill = 0) %>%
  comparison.cloud(colors = c("rosybrown4", "black"),
                   max.words = 40)
Joining, by = "word"

Count the most common positive and negative words (after lemmatization)

lemma_book %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup() %>% group_by(sentiment) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(word, n, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title = 'Most common positive and negative words',
       y = "Contribution to sentiment",
       x = NULL) +
  scale_fill_manual( values = c("red", "purple")) +
  coord_flip()
Joining, by = "word"
